## Ingestion Folder — Two Possible Formats

When sessions have been manually dropped into `ingestion/cursor/projects/`, they may be in one of two formats. **Always check which format is present before running extraction.**

### Format A — JSONL (standard)

```
ingestion/cursor/projects/[slug]/agent-transcripts/[uuid]/[uuid].jsonl
```

Each session is a subdirectory named by its UUID, containing a `.jsonl` file of the same name. Each line of the `.jsonl` file is a JSON object with `role` and `message` fields. Use `scripts/extract_sessions.py` (default mode, no flags needed).

### Format B — Plain-text transcripts (`.txt`)

```
ingestion/cursor/projects/[slug]/agent-transcripts/[uuid].txt
```

Each session is a single `.txt` file directly inside `agent-transcripts/` (no subdirectory). The format uses `user:` / `assistant:` blocks with `<user_query>...</user_query>` tags wrapping each user prompt. **`extract_sessions.py` will silently return 0 sessions for this format** — the script looks for `[uuid]/[uuid].jsonl` subdirectories and won't find plain `.txt` files.

**How to detect:** If `extract_sessions.py` reports `Total sessions: 0` when files are clearly present in the ingestion folder, run:

```
Get-ChildItem -Recurse ingestion\cursor\projects -Filter "*.txt" | Select-Object -First 3
```

If `.txt` files are found, use the fallback script instead. It accepts the same `--days` and `--projects` flags as `extract_sessions.py`:

```
python scripts/extract_txt_sessions.py
python scripts/extract_txt_sessions.py --days 30
python scripts/extract_txt_sessions.py --days 30 --projects slug-a slug-b
```

The output is identical `temp/session_data.json` — all downstream steps (`analyse_sessions.py` onwards) are unchanged.

---

## Context Optimisation — Important

When running the analysis (Step 3 onwards), follow these rules to avoid unnecessary context burn:

**Read `temp/session_data.json` for session content — never the raw source JSONL files.**
`temp/session_data.json` (produced by `extract_sessions.py`) contains only user messages. The raw JSONL files in `~/.cursor/projects/` include full assistant responses which are not needed for scoring and will consume significant context. Look up sampled sessions by `id` from `temp/session_data.json`; the `user_messages` array has everything needed.

**Do not re-read `PROCESS.md` during analysis or report generation.**
`PROCESS.md` covers setup only (Steps 0–3). Once you are past Step 3, load `PROCESS.review.md` for scoring — it contains the full rubric. Load `PROCESS.report.md` for report generation. There is nothing in `PROCESS.md` you need after the scripts have run.

